<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-simple-random-samples" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Simple random samples</title>
     <figure xml:id="fig-srs1">
        <caption>
            Simple random sampling without replacement. Once a member of the population has been selected, it cannot be 
            selected again.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/srs1.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
        A sample is useful only if it represents the population from which it was selected. The method used to select the 
        sample is known as the <em>sampling method</em>, and it plays a fundamental role in statistical inference.
    </p>
    <p>
        To illustrate the idea, consider a population consisting of ten chips labelled <m>a</m> to <m>j</m>, 
        shown on the left of <xref ref="fig-srs1"/>. Four chips are selected at random without returning any chip to the 
        population before the next draw. Because every chip has an equal chance of being selected, this procedure produces 
        a <em>simple random sample without replacement</em>. Repeating the sampling process produces different samples, 
        but every member of the population always has an equal probability of selection.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-brs">
        <caption>
            Biased sampling. Some members of the population are systematically more likely to be selected than others.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/brs.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
        Not every sampling method produces representative data. Suppose only the black chips are deliberately selected, 
        as illustrated in <xref ref="fig-brs"/>. This is an example of <em>biased sampling</em>. 
        Because some members of the population have little or no chance of being selected, the resulting sample does not accurately 
        represent the population and may lead to misleading conclusions.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-srs2">
        <caption>
            Simple random sampling with replacement. Each selected member is returned to the population before the next draw.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/srs2.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
        Another common sampling method is <em>simple random sampling with replacement</em>. After each selection, 
        the chosen chip is returned to the population before the next draw. As shown in <xref ref="fig-srs2"/>, 
        the same member of the population may therefore be selected more than once.
    </p>
    <p>
        In many practical studies, such as surveys and experiments involving people, sampling is usually carried out without 
        replacement because the same individual is rarely included more than once. However, much of statistical theory assumes 
        sampling with replacement because it simplifies the mathematical development. When the population is large, 
        the difference between the two methods is usually negligible. In contrast, the difference between a simple random 
        sample and a biased sample is often substantial and can have a major impact on the validity of statistical conclusions.
    </p>
</subsection>